org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.name: Peaceconferencing
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.blurb: Mediation / Negotiation tool for secondary students to resolve international conflicts.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.introduction:
Welcome to this Peace Conferencing Simulation.

At this portion of the simulation, you will be
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.learning__objvs: This template is used in creating the Bishop's School Peaceconferencing Unit connected to freshman world history classes.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.audience: Instructors, Librarians and Students in High Schools interested in conflict resolution in the global arena.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.planned__play__ideas:
We see this playing out in the course of a school quarter.

The intense portion of this simulation transpires over approximately 3 weeks.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.creator: Skip Cole

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: Mediator
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description: The trained student facilitator of the simulation.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Library Research
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: The first phase of the simulation. Students will begin to discuss world conflicts, and select the conflict they want to work on. They will access scholarly sites and library databases dedicated to providing background to world conflict.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Needs and Fears
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: NEEDS AND FEARS CONFLICT MAPPING Determine the positions, needs and fears of each party in the conflict Access ICG, USIP, other world press sources to determine the players and fill in the chart Share findings with negotiation team (organizational tool needed to pool articles on the overall conflict and specific positions at the table).

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Chat Perspective Positions
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: CHAT PERSPECTIVE POSITIONS IN CONFLICT WITH TEAM Weigh pros and cons for inclusion of each party at the table and then determine the positions that will be represented at the negotiation table, voting choices and record votes.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Determine Your Own Position
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: DETERMINING YOUR OWN POSITION IN THE CONFLICT Using the needs and fears conflict mapping chart and reflection on group chat, select the position at the table that you would like to represent

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Redefine your Position
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes:
REDEFINE YOUR OWN POSITION ON THE CONFLICT MAPPING CHART Merge redefined positions with needs and fears, ready to bring to the table.
Students begin writing position papers.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Getting to the Table
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: GETTING TO THE TABLE Preparation for telling your side of the story ??? Position with needs and fears in more detail with integration of world press

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Brainstorming Solutions
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: CHAT (BRAINSTORMING SOLUTIONS) List all solutions per position in preparation for negotiation table Chat solutions

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Select Solutions
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: SOLUTIONS Parties decide which solutions to try, voting choices and record votes Top priorities emerge to take to the table

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Reaching Consensus
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: REACHING CONSENUS FROM THE MEDIATION-NEGOTIATION TABLE Chat teams understanding of the top priorities presented at the mediation-negotiation table, to include most practical solutions, strategies for achieving peace and accountability, voting choices, record vote

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Formalize Peace Proposal
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: FORMALIZATION OF PEACE PROPOSAL Peace docs, USIP, ICG, UN, other links Chat peace docs, best model for team, voting choices and record votes

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Peace Agreements
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: PEACE AGREEMENTS Open format ??? ability to design peace agreement in the model chosen by team with positions able to interface with actual drafting of the document

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Post-Conflict Peacebuilding
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: POST CONFLICT PEACEBUILDING Chat ideas on how to engage and actively integrate rival positions in a sustained post conflict dialogue

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Completed
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: The last phase of the simulation.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
Peaceconferencing ??? International Flashpoint Research Paper

Due Date:  Wednesday, April 28, periods 4,6,7       Thursday, April 29 period 8

Assignment:

Choose an international flashpoint, i.e.:  Israeli - Palestinian, Pakistan ??? India (Kashmir), Afghanistan, Somalia, Haiti, Nigeria, Iran, North Korea to develop a four to five page research paper, that must include a bibliography and endnotes/footnotes.  You must have at least seven (7) sources or more and approximately 15-20 endnotes/footnotes, note: standard encyclopedias cannot be used as sources on this project (this includes Wikipedia and all other online encyclopedias).  Both works cited and endnotes/footnotes must follow the form of the MLA manual, see Bishop???s Research Guide online for works cited, page 16 and endnotes/footnotes, page 38.

How to Structure Your Paper:

Paragraph One:  Provide a thesis statement with sub-topics of support to substantiate a viable direction for the paper from the position that you will represent at the mediation table, i.e.:  what are the problems facing conflict resolution from your perspective.  Provide subtopics of support to substantiate your thesis that includes a short overview of your conflict from your perspective, analysis of the current situation and probable outcomes for the conflict.

Paragraph Two:  Provide a sub-topic that includes a brief historical account of the situation from your perspective.

Additional Paragraphs:  Provide additional subtopic paragraphs that support your thesis statement (see above). 

Final Paragraph:  Provide a closure that summarizes your assessment and validates your thesis.

All of your sources may come from scholarly internet sites.  Consult articles posted by your team on the Open Simulation Platform, the Bishop???s School Online Resources, and Library page for access to these scholarly sources.  All Internet articles must be included in HARD COPY FORM with information used in your paper HIGHLIGHTED/BOXED-IN AND THE NUMBER OF THE ENDNOTE/FOOTNOTE CLEARLY VISABLE IN THE MARGIN.  Failure to correctly identify endnoted/footnoted material will result in a drastic reduction on the paper.

Due Dates for the Project:

Monday, 4/12/10 Periods 4,6,7   Tuesday,  4/13/10 Period 8     Introduction with thesis and subtopics; brief historical account (paragraphs one and two).  Graded

Friday, 4/16/10 Periods 4,6,7,8  Subtopic Development/additional paragraphs, on to page three.  Graded

Friday, 4/23/10 Periods 4,6,7,8 Peer Evaluation Day, on to page four, with endnotes/footnotes and works cited.  Graded

Due Date:  Wednesday, April 28, periods 4,6,7       Thursday, April 29 period 8

Note:  Make Certain to Create another Copy of Your Paper to Bring to the Negotiation Table, also copies of any articles you think are important because I will have your research papers and articles.

Our Mediation Begins on Thursday, 4/29/10 with Mediator Power Points

org.usip.osp.communications.Event.eventMsgBody: Simplatform Homework: 1) Access world press, USIP, ICG, BBC, Google Conflict 2) Free form page (text box) where each student in class writes down three conflicts with at least three points of information per conflict. Next Day in Class Activity: Pull up pages from each class with conflict suggestions to initiate a short list of favored conflicts. From this list and discussion, select two conflicts per class and allow students to self-select the conflict resolution team that they would like to be on.

Simplatform Homework: 1) Organizational Tool 1) Needs and Fears Chart 2) post articles from world press 3) determine positions 4) Fill in Needs and Fears Chart with all positions. (ability to print chart or show as over head) Next Day in Class Activity - Go over chart and each position with needs and fears in teams

Simplatform Homework: 1) Chat Room - Discuss positions and determine positions that Will be represented at the negotiation table. 2) Voting choices and record. Next Day in Class Activity ??? Determine your own position through face to face discussion.

Simplatform Homework: 1) Organizational Tool : Needs and Fears Chart 2) Each student redefines the position they will represent at the table based on more research and each team creates a new needs and fears chart. (ability to print chart or show as over head) Note: No follow up activity in classroom.
Simplatform Homework: 1) To determine your side of the story (ask students). Next Day in Class Activity ?????? Each side tells story.
Simplatform Homework: 1) Data entry ?????? list positions with solutions Next Day in Class Activity ??? Discuss each position and solution on screen, face to face.

Simulation Homwork: 1) Mediator run 2) Each party/position puts forward short list of top solutions. 3) Voting choice and record. Next Day in Class Activity - Face to face practical solutions, strategies for achieving peace, accountability.

Simplatform Homework: 1) View and chat peace docs. (USIP, ICG, UN, EU, AU, others). 2) Select best model for team, voting choice and record. Next Day Class Activity ??? Peace Agreements Open Format, ability to design peace agreement in the model chosen by team with positions able to interface with actual drafting of document.
